{{For|the earlier queen of Aragon of the same name|Agnes of Aquitaine, Queen of Aragon and Navarre}}
[[File:Inês de Aquitânia, Rainha de Aragão -The Portuguese Genealogy (Genealogia dos Reis de Portugal).png|thumb|Agnes of Aquitaine, taken from ''Genealogia dos Reis de Portugal'' by Antonio de Hollanda.]]
'''Agnes''' ({{lang-fr|Agnès}}, {{lang-es|Inés}}; ''c''.1105–''c''.1159){{sfn|Ubieto Arteta|1987|p=128–32}} was [[Queen consort of Aragon|Queen of Aragon]] during her brief marriage to [[Ramiro II of Aragon|King Ramiro II]], a former monk. The couple separated after the birth of their only child, [[Petronilla of Aragon|Queen Petronilla]], and retired to monasteries. Agnes chose the [[Abbey of Fontevraud]], from where she continued to take part in the affairs of her sons from her first marriage to [[Aimery V, Viscount of Thouars]].

==First marriage==
Agnes was the daughter of [[William IX, Duke of Aquitaine|William IX, Duke of Aquitaine and Count of Poitiers]], and [[Philippa, Countess of Toulouse]]. She was the namesake of her aunt [[Agnes of Aquitaine, Queen of Aragon and Navarre|Agnes]], wife of King [[Peter I of Aragon and Navarre]]. Her first marriage, to [[Aimery V, Viscount of Thouars|Aimery V]], the [[viscount of Thouars]], was celebrated some time prior to 9 January 1117, when the couple confirmed the possessions of the abbey of [[Saint-Laon de Thouars]].{{sfn|Imbert|1876|p=11, no. 8}} Before Aimery's death in 1127, Agnes bore him three sons:{{sfn|Reilly|1998|p=53}}
#William I (died 1151), succeeded his father{{sfn|Ubieto Arteta|1987|p=128–32}}
#Guy (died c. 1149), lord of [[Oiron]]{{sfn|Ubieto Arteta|1987|p=128–32}}
#Geoffrey IV (died 1173), succeeded William{{sfn|Ubieto Arteta|1987|p=128–32}}

==Second marriage==
On 13 November 1135 in the cathedral of [[Jaca]], the ancient capital of the [[Kingdom of Aragon]], Agnes married King [[Ramiro II of Aragon|Ramiro II]], a monk who had resigned the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Barbastro-Monzón|bishopric of Roda]] in order to succeed his childless brother [[Alfonso the Battler]].{{sfn|Reilly|1998|p=53}} The anonymous contemporary author of the ''[[Chronica Adefonsi imperatoris]]'' attributes the initiative in Ramiro's marriage to the Aragonese:
<blockquote>They elected Alfonso's brother king. This man was a monk, and his name was Ramiro. They gave him the sister of the Count of Poitiers for a wife. Even though this was a great sin, the Aragonese did it, for they had lost their king and hoped that there would be an offspring from the royal family. . . King Ramiro went to his wife, and she conceived and gave birth to a daughter. . . He transferred the kingdom to his daughter and acknowledged his sins. He then did penance.{{sfn|Lipskey|1972|p=84 (book I, §62)}}<!--According to the ''[[Gesta comitum Barcinonensium]]'', Ramiro married "a sister of the count of Poitiers" (''sororem comitis Pictaviensis'').--></blockquote>
Agnes' age (approximately thirty) and proven fertility in her prior marriage were probably the main reasons the Aragonese sought her out.{{sfn|Lourie|1975|p=640}} Agnes' brother, [[William X of Aquitaine|Duke William X]], was also one of the few regional supporters of [[Antipope Anacletus II]], who, as the weaker claimant to the papacy, might be persuaded to support Ramiro's irregular (and uncanonical) accession.{{sfn|Reilly|1998|p=53}} Agnes' dowry was a church at [[Loscertales]].

In a document from the same month as his marriage, Ramiro declares that he "took a wife not out of carnal lust, but for the restoration of the blood and the lineage" (''uxorem quoque non carnis libidine, set sanguinis ac proienici restauratione duxi'').{{sfn|Ubieto Arteta|1987|p=128–32}} Later medieval and early modern historians, embarrassed by the disregard for [[canon law]], invented explanations to reconcile the marriage of a bishop with what was current in their own day. The fourteenth-century ''[[Chronicle of San Juan de la Peña]]'' records that messengers were sent to the pope to obtain the proper dispensation.{{sfn|Ubieto Arteta|1987|p=128–32}} The Aragonese translation of the same chronicle places Ramiro's religious status in doubt ("some chronicles say that he was not in holy orders", ''algunas cronónicas dizen que no era en sacres órdenes'').{{sfn|Ubieto Arteta|1987|p=128–32}} At the [[Second Lateran Council]] in 1139, the church, perhaps influenced by the case of Ramiro and Agnes, declared the marriages of clerics to be null and void. Prior to this, they were legitimate, but illegal, marriages.{{sfn|Ubieto Arteta|1987|p=128–32}}

==Queenship==
The first known royal diploma in which Agnes appears as queen is an original dated 29 January 1136.{{sfn|Reilly|1998|p=53}} By August Agnes had born a daughter, [[Petronilla of Aragon|Petronilla]]. Agnes' last appearance in an Aragonese document is from October 1136: a joint donation with her husband of a mill and a horse at Loscertales to the monastery of [[San Pedro de Antefruenzo]].{{sfn|Ubieto Arteta|1987|pp=137–38}} She and Ramiro may have separated shortly after this. Her brother died on a [[Way of Saint James|pilgrimage to Santiago de Compostela]] on 3 April 1137. It was probably during his passage through Iberia that his consent to the proposed marriage of the infant Petronilla was obtained; there is no evidence that Agnes took any part in arranging the future of her daughter.{{sfn|Reilly|1998|p=61}}{{sfn|Ubieto Arteta|1987|pp=137–38}}

In a series of acts between 11 August and 13 November 1137, Ramiro betrothed his daughter to the powerful Count [[Raymond Berengar IV of Barcelona]], made his subjects swear an oath of allegiance to the count and then handed over the royal power to him.{{sfn|Reilly|1998|p=61}} The transfer of power done, Ramiro returned to religious life and Agnes retired to the [[Abbey of Fontevraud]], where her mother had lived. She is recorded there between 1141 and 1147, and there she died around 1159.{{sfn|Fletcher|1984|p=272}}{{sfn|Ubieto Arteta|1987|pp=137–38}}

