Captain '''John Conn''' (c. 5 August 1764 – 4 May 1810) was a senior captain in the [[Royal Navy]], whose career, which included service at the battles of [[battle of the Saintes|the Saintes]], the [[Glorious First of June]], [[battle of Copenhagen (1801)|Copenhagen]] and [[Battle of Trafalgar|Trafalgar]], ended in a shipboard accident before he could reap the rewards of his long service. Conn could also claim membership of [[Horatio Nelson|Nelson's]] "[[Nelson's Band of Brothers|Band of Brothers]]", a clique of dashing naval officers who participated in Nelson's campaigns during the [[French Revolutionary Wars|French Revolutionary]] and [[Napoleonic Wars]], as well as a close friendship with the admiral himself, who once said: "A better or more zealous officer than Captain Conn is not in His Majesty's service."

==Biography==
Born to a Royal Navy [[Warrant officer (United Kingdom)|warrant officer]] of Irish extraction, also named John Conn, he was [[Infant baptism|baptised]] at [[Stoke, Plymouth|Stoke Damerel]], [[Devon]], on 5 August 1764.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~aldo75da/devon.html |title=Conn family of Devon/Cornwall |first1=David |last1=Conn |first2=Martin |last2=Willcocks |work=freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com |year=2013  |accessdate=28 May 2013}}</ref> Conn first went to sea in 1778, aged thirteen, aboard on his father's ship {{HMS|Weazel|1745|2}}, before securing a place on {{HMS|Arrogant|1761|2}} as a [[midshipman]], and in which he saw action at the [[battle of the Saintes]] in April 1782. In 1788 he was made a lieutenant, but had to wait five years before being given a good position,<ref>1 June 1793</ref> using the intervening time to get married to Margaret Nelson, a vicar's daughter. Serving aboard the flagship {{HMS|Royal Sovereign|1786|2}} at the [[Glorious First of June]], he came to the attention of [[Richard Howe, 1st Earl Howe|Admiral Lord Howe]]. He commissioned the 12-gun gun vessel {{HMS|Staunch|1797|2}} in June 1797 but left her a year later. He then further distinguished himself in October 1798 in {{HMS|Foudroyant|1798|2}} at the [[Battle of Tory Island|battle of Donegal]], which resulted in the destruction of a French invasion fleet headed for [[Ireland]]. He was promoted to [[Commander (Royal Navy)|commander]] on 11 August 1800 and took command of the [[bomb vessel]] {{HMS|Discovery|1789|2}}. At the first [[battle of Copenhagen (1801)|battle of Copenhagen]] his expertise caused terrible damage to the Danish fleet. Next, he participated in Nelson's bold but disastrous [[Raids on Boulogne|attack on the French invasion force]] in [[Boulogne-sur-Mer|Boulogne]] shortly afterwards, commanding the division of gun-boats, and gaining his commanding officer's attention and respect.

Conn received promotion to [[post-captain]] on 29 August 1802 and took command of {{HMS|Culloden|1783|2}}. His nine-year-old son Henry joined him on ''Culloden''. Conn then transferred to the French prize {{HMS|Canopus|1798|2}} and joined Nelson in the [[Mediterranean]] at Nelson's request. In 1805 Conn was given temporary command of the [[first rate]] flagship {{HMS|Victory||2}} and his old ship ''Royal Sovereign'' whilst their commanders were on leave; his performance further contributed to his reputation as a reliable and steady officer. On 10 October he returned the ''Royal Sovereign'' to [[Cuthbert Collingwood|Admiral Collingwood]] and took command of the fast new [[second rate]] {{HMS|Dreadnought|1801|2}}.

Eleven days later Conn and his crew were thrown into battle as the Franco-Spanish fleet attempted to break out of [[Cadiz]]. Situated halfway down Collingwood's division, Conn struggled to reach the action, only getting there around the time Nelson was mortally wounded in the northern division. Making up for the delay, ''Dreadnought'' tangled with the {{Ship|Spanish ship|San Juan Nepomuceno||2|up=yes}}, rescuing the battered {{HMS|Bellerophon|1786|2}}, killing the Spanish captain [[Cosme Damián de Churruca y Elorza|Cosmé Damián Churruca]] and forcing his ship to surrender. Charging on from this victory, the ''Dreadnought'' engaged the Spanish flagship {{Ship|Spanish ship|Principe de Asturias|1794|2}}, mortally wounding the Spanish admiral [[Federico Carlos Gravina y Nápoli|Gravina]], but being unable to defeat the enemy, which succeeded in escaping back to Cadiz. Conn even managed to rescue his prize, the ''San Juan Nepomuceno'' being one of only four captured enemy ships to survive the storm.

Following the battle, in which ''Dreadnought'' suffered 33 casualties, Conn continued in service taking over the massive 112 gun {{HMS|San Josef||2}} and then the 120 gun {{HMS|Hibernia|1804|2}} as flag captain before moving as a [[Commodore (Royal Navy)|commodore]] to the [[West Indies]] in {{HMS|Swiftsure|1804|2}} in 1810. Admiral's rank and the honours which came with it were surely not far away when tragedy struck on 4 May when during the chase of a small French ship near [[Bermuda]], Conn became over-eager, slipped and fell overboard. ''Swiftsure'' was halted and a search was conducted, but Conn had drowned before help arrived. His passing was mourned in Britain and especially in the Navy where he was a popular and respected figure. Sir [[John Borlase Warren]], an old commander and friend, expressed regret at the death of "so deserving an officer as Captain Conn."

