The '''SS ''Hydrus''''' was an American steel-hulled [[Great Lakes]] [[bulk carrier|bulk freighter]], constructed in 1903 and launched as the '''''R.E. Schuck'''''.<ref>{{Cite web |title = Hydrus, 1913. |work = Fr. Edward J. Dowling, S.J. Marine Historical Collection |publisher = University of Detroit Mercy |url = http://www.dalnet.lib.mi.us/gsdl/cgi-bin/library?e=d-000-00---0shipping--00-0-0-0prompt-10---4---Document---0-1l--1-en-50---20-help---001-011-1-0utfZz-8-0&a=d&c=shipping&cl=CL1.8.36&d=HASH01f4241b23872b29c34a585e |accessdate = 31 October 2010 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110716062605/http://www.dalnet.lib.mi.us/gsdl/cgi-bin/library?e=d-000-00---0shipping--00-0-0-0prompt-10---4---Document---0-1l--1-en-50---20-help---001-011-1-0utfZz-8-0&a=d&c=shipping&cl=CL1.8.36&d=HASH01f4241b23872b29c34a585e |archivedate = 16 July 2011 |df = }}</ref> She was following the [[SS James Carruthers|SS ''James Carruthers'']] heading south on Lake Huron while carrying a load of [[iron ore]] when she and the ''Carruthers'' were caught in the [[Great Lakes Storm of 1913]].<ref>{{Cite web |last = Willis |first = Glen |title = The great storm of 1913 |publisher = Pointe Aux Barques Lighthouse Society |date = 2003 |url = http://www.pointeauxbarqueslighthouse.org/preserve/shipwrecks/1913storm.cfm |accessdate = 31 October 2010 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100527181317/http://www.pointeauxbarqueslighthouse.org/preserve/shipwrecks/1913storm.cfm |archivedate = 27 May 2010 |df = }}</ref>
The ''Hydrus'' foundered and sank with a crew of twenty-four aboard on or around 8 November 1913<ref>{{cite news |author=Jim Schaefer |title=Man discovers Lake Huron shipwreck missing since 1913 |date=November 9, 2015 |work=[[Detroit Free Press]] |url=http://www.freep.com/story/news/2015/11/09/shipwreck-hunter-finds-ghost-great-storm-1913/75332346/ |accessdate = 2015-11-09 }}</ref> while heading for the [[St. Clair River]]. During the storm, waves were said to be 35 feet high along with wind gusts of 90 miles per hour.<ref>{{Cite web | last = Swayze | first = Dave | title = Great Lakes Shipwrecks H - Hydrus | work = The Great Lakes Shipwreck File: Total Losses of Great Lakes Ships 1679 - 1999 | publisher = [[Boatnerd]] | date = 1998–2001 | url = http://www.boatnerd.com/swayze/shipwreck/h.htm | accessdate =31 October 2010 }}</ref> Five of the crew were found frozen to death in a lifeboat that washed ashore in Canada. The ''James Carruthers'' was also lost in the storm as well as the [[SS Argus|SS ''Argus'']], which was the sister ship of the ''Hydrus''. The wreck of the ''Hydrus'' was located in the summer of 2015 by a team of shipwreck hunters led by David Trotter.<ref>{{cite news |author=Jim Schaefer |title=Man discovers Lake Huron shipwreck missing since 1913 |date=November 9, 2015 |work=[[Detroit Free Press]] |url=http://www.freep.com/story/news/2015/11/09/shipwreck-hunter-finds-ghost-great-storm-1913/75332346/ |accessdate = 2015-11-09 }}</ref>
